lling account of how scores, metrics, and standardized research evaluations altered the incentives of scientists and administrators by rewarding forms of scholarship that were closer to established disciplinary canons. In doing so, research evaluations amplified publication hierarchies and long-standing forms of academic prestige to the detriment of diversity. Slowly but surely, they reshaped academic departments, the interests of scholars, the organization of disciplines, and the employment conditions of researchers.Critiquing the effects of quantification on the workplace, this book also presents alternatives to existing forms of evaluation, calling for new forms of vocational solidarity that can challenge entrenched inequality in academia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aEducational evaluationzGreat BritainxManagement. 0aEducational evaluation-Great Britain-Management. 0aHigher education and statezGreat Britain. 0aHigher education and state-Great Britain. 0aSocial sciencesxStudy and teaching (Higher)xResearchzGreat Britain. 0aSocial sciencesxStudy and teaching (Higher)zGreat BritainxResearch. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aREF.  aResearch Excellence Framework.  aassessment.  ahigher education.  asociology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074966340uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/pard1978040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231552356423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231552356/original  a978-3-11-074966-3  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK